# Lesson 2: Dim an LED

## 2.1 Overview

In this lesson you will learn how to control the brightness of an LED.

## 2.2 Components required

* Development board
* 1 x LED
* 1 x 150 Ω resistor
* Breadboard 830p
* 2 x male-to-male jumper wire
* Micro USB – Type A USB Cable

## 2.3 Theory
### Pulse Width Modulation (PWM)

   **PWM** is a modulation technique used to control the speed of motors or the
brightness of LEDs. **PWM** creates a square wave by switching between on and off.

   The value that characterizes the PWM is the **Duty Cycle**. It represents the
duration in which the voltage is kept on. For example, 25% duty cycle means that 25%
of the period the voltage is high and 75% of the period the voltage is low. The PWM
frequency is about 1000 Hz, so the period is about 1 ms.

   The duty cycle can be set using the instruction **"pwm.duty(value)"**.The variable "pwm" 
is previously declared as such **"pwm = PWM(LED)"** and the "value" is stored on 10 bits, 
so 0 coresponds to 0% duty cycle and 1023 coresponds to 100% duty cycle.

![pwm.png](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

## 2.4 Connection

You have to connect the negative terminal to a GND pin of the development board, and
the positive terminal to a digital pin. In this example, we are going to use D6, as
shown below.

![dev_board.png](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Below, you can find a visual representation of the connections:

![board.png](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

The board runs at 3.3 V, which is enough to power the LED. In order to power
the board, you have to plug the USB cable to a computer or to a travel adapter. It has
an onboard 3.3 V regulator, which lowers the voltage from 5 V to 3.3 V. The resistor is
picked accordingly to the equation presented before (check the Resistor section). The
required resistance is about 120 Ω, but we are going to pick a 150 Ω resistor as the
120 Ω is not a common value.

## 2.5 Code

### Import libraries
First, we import libraries to later use the functions and variables predefined in them.

#use these libraries to declare used pins and PWM
from machine import Pin, PWM
#use these libraries for delay
from time import sleep

### Declaring variables
We declare the variables used with the corresponding pins. We declare the LED as the output pin ('Pin.OUT') and we will look at the pin diagram and notice 
that pin D6 is GPIO**12**.
We also declare the pwm for LED to create fluctuating energy.

#first, define the pins used by the led
LED = Pin(12, Pin.OUTPUT) #D6
#and the pwm for led
pwm = PWM(LED)

### Infinite loop

We will create an infinite loop for the board to execute the instructions continuously.

In the this while loop we will use the duty cycle; to set the brightness on the LED. 
    
The value can be from 0 (0% duty cycle, which means that the LED is off) to 1023 (100% duty cycle and the LED will be at maximumbrightness).

Using a for loop we will set the value from 0 to 1023 with a delay of 2 milliseconds to have time to see the fading.
Also we are using another for loop to set the value from 1023 to 0 with a delay of 2 milliseconds. 
    
The first for loop is used to set the brightness of the LED from 0% to 100%, and the second is used to set the brightness from 100% to 0%.

#for board execute the instructions continuously we make an infinite loop
while True:
    #PWM is generated using 10 bits, so it ranges between
    #0 and 1023 (2^10 = 1024)
    for fade in range(0, 1024):
        #set the brightness of the LED using duty cycle
        pwm.duty(fade)
        #wait 0.005 seconds
        sleep(0.005)
    #keep the LED at the maximum brightness for 500 ms  
    sleep(0.05)
    
    #we reduce the intensity of the led
    for fade in range(1024, -1, -1):
        #set the brightness of the LED using duty cycle
        pwm.duty(fade)
        #wait 0.005 seconds
        sleep(0.005)

Next step is to gently connect the development board to the computer via the
included micro USB cable. There is only one way to plug it in, do not use force to
insert the cable.

To compile the code you should follow the instructions for the board *Adafruit CLUE* from this link:
https://youtu.be/F_4GXU8kKfk?t=585

**Congratulations**, you have completed the tutorial!
